India's New Hope
Cambridge, USA—India's latest election may be the most significant positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Indian National Congress, which had ruled India almost continuously since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be pleased with this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of Rajiv Gandhi, former prime minister and leader of the Indian National Congress, has been effectively ruling from behind the scenes since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh is merely a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Indian National Congress pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led to India's annual economic growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP is still hovering around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected prime minister, Narendra Modi, promised during his campaign to bring rapid growth in employment and income across all of India, as he did when he served as chief minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, expanding economic activity and attracting commercial investment from both within India and abroad.
A significant feature of the latest election is that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which can be considered an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties in order to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will lend Modi a hand in his economic plan.
The newly appointed finance minister, Arun Jaitley, has extensive political experience and previously held ministerial positions in the earlier BJP government.
Jaitley is also renowned as a strategic thinker known for his sympathy towards business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (the central bank). Rajan is an outstanding economist who, during his tenure as Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, demonstrated a desire to reduce India's double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities they offer, as primary and secondary education in India is highly underdeveloped.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy at the primary school level.
Teachers themselves have inadequate education and lack motivation, and many teachers never even show up at the schools where they are supposed to teach.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products across the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private airlines and airports indicates that private enterprises can also make significant contributions in this field.
Fiscal consolidation.
Large budget deficits are absorbing national savings that could otherwise be used to expand business investment. Budget deficits have led to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
The inefficient operation of manufacturing and other industries owned by the Indian government often results in the erosion of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Cut subsidies.
Power and energy subsidies have led to wasteful overconsumption and an increase in fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, due to the implementation of a notable new fingerprint-based cash transfer system, India's cash transfer efficiency is relatively high.
Agricultural Reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result was a large accumulation of goods in warehouses, while production incentives were misdirected.
Agricultural markets should be privatized.
Property rights and regional demarcation.
As long as you have visited Mumbai or other major Indian cities, you will see that regional demarcation restrictions lead to poor urban land use, constraining the initial dilution.
Unclear property rights, especially regarding agricultural land, have hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Ease foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign companies cannot be majority shareholders in banks and insurance companies.
Easing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex national and state sales tax system distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a sharing tax system has been ongoing for a long time and should now move into the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases have undermined economic confidence and hindered officials' decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by small-scale corruption, with bribery having become a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and restrict small-scale corruption through a new cash transfer system.
Driven by expectations of stronger growth and increased profits, India's stock market has risen 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their election promises.
